The wolf tries not his wiles around the sheepfold, nor prowls by night about the flocks3 a keener care tames him. Timorous deer and shy stags now stray among the hounds and about the houses. Yea, the brood of the great deep, and all swimming things, like shipwreckcd corpses. are washed up by the waves on the verge of the shore3 in strange wise sea—calves flee to the rivers. The viper, too, vainly defended in her winding lairs, perishes, and the water-snake, his scales erect in terror. The air is unkind even to the birds ; headlong they fall, leaving life beneath the clouds on high. Fui-ther, even change of pasture avails no more3 the remedies sought work barm ; masters in the art fail, Chiron, son of Phillyra, and Melampus, Amythaon’s son. Ghastly Tisiphone rages, and, let forth into light from Stygiam gloom, drives before her Disease and Dread, while day by day, uprising, she rears still higher her greedy head. The rivers and thirsty banks and sloping hills echo to the bleating of floeks and incessant lowing of kine. And now in droves she deals out death, and in the very stalls piles up the bodies, rotting with putrid foulncss, till nien learn to cover them in earth and bury them in pits.
